observations.managementAction:
AAR 2020 AO No. 3 | The Municipality continued to make significant efforts to adhere to the framework prescribed by R.A. No. 10121 regarding the appropriation and utilization of the 5% LDRRMF;
The BAC Secretariat has already made available all necessary procurement data for all emergency purchases.

The Municipal Accountant observed the proper accounting of inventoriable items.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:

a) justify the non-observance of the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 in the hiring of the five confidential consultants;

(b) require the said consultants to submit personal data sheet and work credentials for the buildup of their data base;

(c) require the HRMO to formulate, for his approval, a written policy/guideline to serve as standards in the hiring of consultants in the future; and

(d) evaluate the necessity of renewing the current consulting contracts in view of the apparent duplication of functions.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Accounting employee concerned to:

(a) continue exerting efforts to locate the documents pertaining to the above receivables; 

(b) provide the details in the subsidiary ledger of individual debtors; 

(c) send Demand Letters or Collection Letter to the employees and external entities with outstanding balance at year-end; and 

(d) set-up the Allowance for Doubtful Accounts to fairly present the value of the collectibles of the agency.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive would instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Market Supervisor to –

send out letters to market lessees requesting for the updating of the rental payments on market stalls occupied by them; 

remind the lessees of the provisions of the Market Code of Llanera 2017, particularly in paying the rentals on a timely manner and the consequences of not paying within the prescribed period;

to conduct immediate inventory of all existing market stall for rent to determine the existing lessees of the market stall to facilitate the execution of the contract of lease;

establish a system of collection to be enforced in the actual collection of market stall rental fee periodically and demand for the collection of unpaid rental fees; and

maintain individual subsidiary ledgers of the market stall lessees for easy monitoring and enforcing of collection and strict implementation of the contract lease.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) issue an Executive Order to include the SK Chairperson as part of the MSWMB; 

(b) instruct the MSWMB to: (i) create specific plan/target for the ensuing years together with its guidelines and mechanics;

(ii) involve closely all the Barangay Officials in the strict implementation of the existing environmental laws; and 

(iii) strengthen the Information and Education Campaign (IEC) especially on “proper waste segregation”, “no segregation, no collection policy” and “no littering policy” among citizens; and

(c) take immediate action towards the proper disposal of wastes that were not covered by the CY 2018 MOA with MCWMC.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the concerned officials/employees to: 

(a) ensure that the expenses incurred for the programs and activities have properly authorized appropriations; 

(b) provide the required trainings/seminars to the members of GFPS to aid them in the proper discharge of their duties and responsibilities; 

(c) instruct the GFPS to review the GPB to determine PPAs that are responsive to gender gaps or issues; 

(d) issue an Executive Order to comply with the required structure and composition of GFPS; and 

(e) create M&E team that will assess the overall effectiveness and efficiency of their gender mainstreaming efforts.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive would instruct the Municipal Treasurer and Market Supervisor to –
send out letters to market lessees requesting for the updating of the rental payments on market stalls occupied by them;
remind the lessees of the provisions of the Market Code of Llanera 2017, particularly in paying the rentals on a timely manner and the consequences of not paying within the prescribed period;
to conduct immediate inventory of all existing market stall for rent to determine the existing lessees of the market stall to facilitate the execution of the contract of lease;
establish a system of collection to be enforced in the actual collection of market stall rental fee periodically and demand for the collection of unpaid rental fees; and
maintain individual subsidiary ledgers of the market stall lessees for easy monitoring and enforcing of collection and strict implementation of the contract lease.

We recommended and the management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct: 

(a) all heads of offices concerned to include the PPMPs of all projects, programs and activities that will be prioritized by the Municipality for a given year; 

(b) the BAC Secretariat to consolidate these requirements in the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) that is compliant with the required format; 



(c) the Engineering Office and MPDC to (i) ensure that the requisite conditions and authority are met before implementing projects by administration; and (ii) coordinate in the planning for, implementation and monitoring of said projects; and 

(d) the Accounting Office to ascertain completeness of the required documents before payments related to said projects are made. 

Likewise, we advised, which Management conformed, that the LCE formally designate all key personnel in project implementation and clearly define their duties and responsibilities to avoid confusion and miscommunication.

We recommended that the management instruct the MSWDO to: 

(a) secure the signed and notarized Supplemental Memorandum of Agreement from the DSWD Regional Office III; 



(b) provide the reports of assistances showing the actual cash and construction materials given to the beneficiaries; 




(c) provide justification for not procuring the construction materials through public bidding in compliance with the R.A. 9184; and 




(d) present the explanation on the discrepancies noted above in the manner on which the “Emergency Shelter Assistance” Program was carried out.
